Date: 03 Nov 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Australian Broadcast Co. 11/03/00
<http://www.abc.net.au/news/science/health/2000/11/item20001103094022_1.htm>

France Considers Bonemeal Ban
-----------------------------
As 2 new cases of bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), or mad cow
disease, have been reported in western France, the French Government is
considering a ban on bonemeal in all animal feed. The new cases were
detected in the Cotes d'Armor region of western Brittany.
The cows were born in September 1995 and November 1994. The herds to which
they belonged were to be slaughtered. The 2 new finds bring to 84 the total
number of BSE cases so far this year, and 164 since statistics were first
recorded in 1991.
As the new cases were announced, the French Government awaits the outcome
of scientific and economic studies before ruling on the use of bonemeal in
all animal feed. The ban at present only applies to cattle feed.
Consumer associations and politicians, including President Jacques Chirac,
have called for the existing ban on the use of animal matter to be extended
to all animal feeds, not just cattle feed. The Government said it was
taking time to study the financial implications of a total ban before
considering the advice of the French food safety agency.
