Date: 06 Nov 2000
From: Chris Griot <christian.griot@ivi.admin.ch>
Source: Associated Press 6 Nov 2000 [edited
<http://www.roaringpenguin.com/mimedefang/>

Switzerland Considers Restrictions on Livestock Feed
--------------------------------------------------
Swiss authorities said they are considering banning animal products in all
livestock feed in a bid to stamp out so-called mad cow disease or bovine
spongiform encephalopathy (BSE).
The Federal Veterinary Office said it was drawing up proposals as a result
of 2 new confirmed cases of the disease this week among cattle born after
stringent controls were introduced in 1996.
Switzerland became the second country after Britain to report cases of BSE
in the earlier 1990s. The government ordered the slaughter of all affected
herds, including offspring of infected cows, in 1996 and it banned the use
of animal by-products in cattle feed.
Experts were stunned by the new cases, given the precautions taken thus
far. "We're in a quandary and we don't know the way out," said Ulrich Kihm,
director of the veterinary office. "But we don't dare wait for 5 more years
before taking action."
The proposed ban -- which would cover all animal bone meal and most fats in
feed destined for animals -- will now be submitted to the cabinet for
action. Officials estimated the measures would cost 50 to 60 million Swiss
francs ($29 to $34 million US).
France is also studying the prospect of a total ban on animal byproducts in
livestock feed after an upsurge in cases of BSE and a nationwide scare that
infected meat may have been sold by a leading supermarket.
