[4
Date: 07 Nov 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Australian Broadcast news, 7 Nov 2000 [edited
<http://www.abc.net.au/news/newslink/nat/newsnat-7nov2000-74.htm>

Mad Cow Disease Outbreak Feared in France
-------------------------------------------
The French Health secretary has warned that the country faces an outbreak
of "several dozen cases" of the deadly variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease
(vCJD), the human version of mad cow disease.
Dominique Gillot says there had so far been just 2 confirmed cases of the
human version of the deadly disease.
Mrs Gillot said that the number of people displaying symptoms of the
disease was already on the rise. Alarm about BSE has been spreading in
France since a report that cattle from an infected herd had been
unwittingly bought by supermarkets and 8 tons of the meat had been put on
sale.
******
[5
Date: 07 Nov 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Yahoo News, 7 Nov 2000 [edited
<http://asia.dailynews.yahoo.com/headlines/world/article.html?s=asia/headlin
es/001107/world/afp/Chirac_calls_for_immediate_ban_on_bone_meal_in_animal_fe
ed.html>

French Bone Meal Ban Urged
-----------------------------------------------
French President Jacques Chirac called for an immediate ban on meat and
bone meal (MBM) in animal feed because of fears over mad cow disease
(Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy or BSE). "We must ban animal meal
without any delay, and move towards a systematic tracing program in order
to limit the risks of contamination by BSE," he said on French television.
Feed manufactured from the ground carcasses of animals is regarded as the
most likely vector for BSE. It is banned as cattle feed in France, but
permitted for poultry and pigs.
Alarm about BSE has reached new heights in France in the last 2 weeks,
after it was revealed that cattle from a herd infected with BSE had been
sold to supermarkets.
